      "3pi-v2"
    ],
    "role": "Third-Party Risk Management (TPRM) and Compliance Data Source"
  },
  "sections": [
    {
      "heading": "Overview",
      "content": "[[OneTrust]] is a specialized Third-Party Risk Management (TPRM) system used to conduct compliance reviews, manage vendor risk profiles, and serve as a primary data source for Third-Party Interest (TPI) assessments. Within the organizational architecture, it functions as a critical decision-making engine where compliance officers review vendor documentation and assign terminal statuses such as 'Approved' or 'Not a TPI'. The system is designed to capture qualitative and quantitative risk data, which is then intended to be synchronized with downstream enterprise systems to maintain a consistent global risk posture.\n\nThe core capabilities of [[OneTrust]] include automated risk assessment workflows, centralized vendor data management, and the facilitation of compliance-driven data triggers. Strategically, the system is vital because it acts as the 'source of truth' for vendor compliance status. Without the accurate capture of data within [[Onetrast]], the organization faces significant risks regarding data integrity between compliance decisions and operational execution. If the data in [[OneTrust]] is not properly formatted or populated, it creates bottlenecks in the automated pipeline, preventing critical updates from reaching downstream systems.\n\nIn the broader enterprise architecture, [[OneTrust]] sits upstream of the primary operational platforms. It receives inputs from internal audit findings and vendor-provided documentation, processes these through human-in-the-loop review workflows, and produces structured outputs. These outputs are intended to flow into [[Aravo]] and [[Salesforce]] to update vendor flags and trigger automated workflows. The integrity of the entire compliance ecosystem depends on the successful transition of data from the manual review phase in [[OneTrust]] to the automated execution phase in downstream systems."
    },
    {
      "heading": "History & Context",
      "content": "The evolution of [[OneTrust]] within the organization is closely tied to the transition from manual, email-driven compliance processes to an automated, API-enabled ecosystem. Historically, the 'before' state was characterized by fragmented communication, where compliance updates were handled via manual outreach and informal documentation. This led to significant data mismatches, such as the incident identified on February 10, 2026, where suppliers marked as active TPIs in [[OneTrust]] had already been deactivated in [[Aravo]] since June 2025. This discrepancy highlighted the urgent need for a more robust, synchronized system-to-system integration.\n\nThe decision to formalize the [[OneTrust]] workflows was driven by the need to resolve these systemic mismisos. Early in the project lifecycle, specifically around February 27, 2026, the drafting of the Business Requirements Document (BRD) for 'Initiative #7658 - 3P Cyber - API Integration' marked a pivotal shift toward technical automation. This initiative sought to move away from the manual 'OHD' (Office of Head of Department) updates and toward a controlled, automated trigger mechanism. The architects of this transition, including the [[Optimize Solutions]] team and the [[Anti-CorruptionDD]] group, aimed to eliminate the human error inherent in manual status updates.\n\nAs the project progressed into March 2026, the focus shifted to resolving 'stuck' records caused by incomplete data entry. On March 3, 2026, the team identified a significant bottleneck involving 30 vendor records that were stuck in the pipeline due to missing data. This event underscored the importance of the system's data contracts. The evolution of [[OneTrust]] from a standalone review tool to a critical component of an integrated pipeline has been shaped by these real-world operational challenges, moving the system toward a state where compliance decisions can trigger immediate, automated actions across the enterprise."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Technical Details",
      "content": "The technical operation of [[OneTrust]] revolves around a structured data pipeline that requires specific field population to trigger downstream synchronization. The system utilizes custom fields to act as gates for the automated pipeline. A primary technical artifact is the `tpi_comments` field (also identified as `customField1158`). This field serves as a mandatory validation check; even if a vendor has a terminal status like 'Approved' or 'Not a TPI', the automated pipeline will not pick up the record for sync to [[Aravo]] or [[Salesforce]] unless `tpi_comments` is populated with qualitative data. This ensures that every automated status change is backed by a human-readable audit trail.\n\nData flow within the system follows a specific logic: once a compliance officer completes a review, the record enters a 'terminal' state. For certain use cases, such as the 'False Positive' workflow, the `supplier_is_false_positive` field must also be populated to ensure correct routing. The pipeline is designed with a retry logic, specifically a 2-hour automated cycle. Once the required fields (like `tpi_comments`) are updated, the system's integration layer automatically detects the change and pushes the data to downstream systems. This 'pull-and-push' mechanism is intended to replace manual email-based updates with a reliable API-driven trigger.\n\nIn the future-state architecture, the system is designed to support two primary use cases via API. In 'Use Case 1' (TPI to non-TPI), [[OneTrust]] sends an API trigger to [[Aravo]] to automatically update the TPI flag. In 'Use Case 2' (Non-TPI to TPI), the trigger initiates an automated compliance workflow in [[Aravo]]. The deployment model relies on these structured data contracts to maintain integrity. The technical dependency is bidirectional: [[OneTrust]] requires accurate vendor master data to perform reviews, and [[Aravo]] requires the validated outputs from [[One-Trust]] to maintain accurate risk flags. The scale of this operation involves managing hundreds of vendor records, where the failure to meet the data contract (e.g., leaving `customField1158` empty) results in immediate pipeline blockage."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Key Relationships",
      "content": "The [[OneTrust]] system is central to a complex web of human and technical stakeholders. The primary owners and operators are the [[Anti-CorruptionDD]] team and the [[OneTrust]] team, specifically individuals like [[Rijul Kalra]] and [[Leobardo Mora]], who manage the heavy lifting of data validation and pipeline troubleshooting. The [[Anti-CorruptionDD]] team acts as the primary user group, responsible for the qualitative input that satisfies the system's data contracts. They interact with the system by performing reviews and populating the necessary fields to unblock the automated pipeline.\n\nTechnically, the most critical relationship is between [[OneTrust]] and [[Aravo]]. This is a system-to-system integration where [[One-Trust]] acts as the decision-making engine and [[Aravo]] acts as the operational system of record. The relationship is defined by an API-enabled workflow where [[One-Trust]] pushes compliance results to [[Aravo]] to update vendor risk flags. Another vital relationship exists with [[Salesforce]], which receives the synchronized data for commercial and procurement use. Without this link, the compliance decisions made in [[One-Trust]] would remain siloed and ineffective for the broader business.\n\nInternal stakeholders such as [[Pankaj Arora]] and [[Deepti Zimmerman]] oversee the strategic alignment of these systems. [[Pankaj Arora]] acts as a bridge between the technical implementation and the strategic goals of the [[Optimize Solutions]] team, ensuring that the API integration meets the requirements of the [[3pi-v2]] project. [[Deepti Zimmerman]] represents the business-side oversight, focusing on the auditability and accuracy of the data being moved between systems. Finally, the [[Cyber Security Team]], led by individuals like [[Graham Holton]] and [[Tobias Dietrich]], manages the [[OneTrust TPRM]] module used for Vendor Security Assessments (VSA), representing a specialized user group that relies on the system's integrity for risk management. This network of relationships ensures that the data flowing through [[One-Trust]] is both accurate and actionable."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Current Status",
      "content": "As of mid-March 2026, the [[One-Trust]] system is in a state of active transition and troubleshooting. The primary focus is the resolution of the '30 TPI records stuck' incident, which was first flagged on March 3, 2026. While many records have been resolved, 8 specific vendors remain blocked in the pipeline due to the missing `tpi_comments` (`customField1158`) field. This is an active workstream involving [[Leobardo Mora]] and the [[Anti-CorruptionDD]] team to ensure these records are successfully synced to [[Aravo]] and [[Salesforce]].\n\nAnother significant operational context is the ongoing 'Initiative #7658' regarding the 3P Cyber API Integration. This workstream aims to finalize the automated transition from manual updates to the API-enabled workflow. While the transition to [[Aravo]] production was noted as progressing on March 19, 2026, the full enablement of the [[One-Trust]] side of the integration is pending the return of key personnel from working sessions. The current status is one of high-intensity data cleanup to ensure the automated pipeline can function without manual intervention."
    },
    {
      "heading": "Open Questions",
      "content": "Several unresolved architectural and operational questions remain. First, there is a need to verify the exact synchronization logic for the `supplier_is_false_positive` field; it is unclear if this field is a prerequisite for all 'Not a TPI' status changes or only for specific edge cases. Second, the discrepancy between [[Aravo]] deactivations and [[One-Trust]] active statuses (as noted in the February 10, 2026, audit) suggests a potential gap in the reverse-sync logic that needs investigation. Finally, the long-term stability of the 2-hour retry cycle as a primary mechanism for data consistency remains an open question. To complete this article, we would need more granular detail on the API error-handling protocols and a full mapping of all custom fields used in the [[3pi-v2]] project."
    }
  ],
